Weekly Sales Forecast for Big Box, Inc.¶

Big Box, Inc. requested a forecast of weekly sales for the individual deparments in each of its stores. The company provided the data team with three CSV files containing data related to its stores and their departments, weekly sales, and economic and weather conditions in the geographic areas where stores are located. Specifically Big Box requested a forecast of the next three months beyond the actual sales data provided.

We performed a time series analysis through the following phases:

Time Series Analysis Phases¶

  1. Data Import, Validation, and Merge
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis: Stores, Departments, and Total Sales
  3. Exploratory Data Analysis: Weekly Sales
  4. Feature Creation and Selection
  5. Modeling and Prediction: Random Forest Regression
  6. Modeling and Prediction: SARIMA

Phase 5. Modeling and Prediction: Random Forest Regression¶

We used the RandomForestRegressor from the Python scikit-learn library for our model.

Choosing the Number of Estimators¶

We tested different models by selecting different numbers of decision tree estimators (20, 30, 40, and 50). We saw that between 20 and 30 estimators there was a decrease in RMSE and an increase in R-Square. However continuing to increase the number of estimators beyond 30 did not appear to improve the performance further. Therefore we chose the model containing 30 estimators and proceeded with the analysis.

A sample run of the model generated these performance metrics including 95% accuracy (R-square):

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE) = 24004879
  • Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) = 4899
  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE) = 2230
  • R-square = 0.9511

Model Fitting and Evaluation¶

We prepared our training features and target values (x_train, y_train) as well as our validation features and target values (x_test, y_test). We then fit our model and used it to generate weekly sales predictions for the weeks in the validation set. We calculate several metrics to gauge how close the predicted sales were to the actual sales.

One prediction run produced the following overall metrics for all stores and all departments, including an accuracy of 95% (R-square = 0.95) which is very good.

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE) = 24004879
  • Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) = 4899
  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE) = 2230
  • R-square = 0.9511

NOTE: The metrics should also be examined for model performance on individual stores and deparments.

y_train = trainingset['Weekly_Sales']

#Separate the features from the target values in the validation set
x_test = validationset.copy(deep=True)
x_test = x_test.drop(['Weekly_Sales'], axis=1)
y_test = validationset['Weekly_Sales']
In [8]:
#Use 30 estimators to fit our model
estimator_count = 30
regression = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=estimator_count)
regression.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_pred = regression.predict(x_test)
In [9]:
#Calculate and print performance metrics
metric_mean_sqr_err = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
metric_root_mean_sqr_err = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
metric_mean_abs_err = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
metric_r2_score = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print('Mean Squared Error (MSE) = ' + "{:.0f}".format(metric_mean_sqr_err))
print('Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) = ' + "{:.0f}".format(metric_root_mean_sqr_err))
print('Mean Absolute Error (MAE) = ' + "{:.0f}".format(metric_mean_abs_err))
print('R-square = ' + "{:.4f}".format(metric_r2_score))

Comparing Predicted Versus Actual Sales¶

We created a function to plot predicted versus actual weekly sales. We created one plot to compare the predictions against the validation set. Then we created a second plot to visualize the predictions against the entire range of available dates. Here we examined the same three departments that we analyzed in the Exploratory Data Analysis phase:

  • For Store 1 Department 1, the model did well in predicting the steep drop in sales in late April, although the drop in predicted sales occurs approximately 2 weeks after the actual drop.

  • For Store 5 Department 26, the model predicted the gradual decrease in sales in April and May. The predicted sales in June and July remain a little higher than the actual sales in these months.

  • For Store 33 Department 80, the predicted sales do not have the weekly fluctuations that appear in the actual sales. However the predictions lie between the peaks and troughs of the actual sales from April through June. Where the lower peak occurs in mid July, the predicted sales also drops.

In [11]:
#Function to plot predicted vs actual weekly sales
#for one deparment in one store
def plot_pred_vs_actual_sales_for_onestore(actualdates,
                                           actualsales,
                                           preddates,
                                           predsales,
                                           storenum,
                                           deptnum,
                                           x_date_spacing=1):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.xlabel('Week')
    plt.ylabel('Weekly Sales ($)')
    plt.title('Actual and Predicted Weekly Sales for Store #' + str(storenum) +
              " Dept #" + str(deptnum))
    plt.xticks(np.arange(0, len(actualsales)+1, x_date_spacing))    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)    
    plt.plot(actualdates,
             actualsales,
             label='Actual Weekly Sales')
    plt.plot(preddates,
             predsales, 
             label='Predicted Weekly Sales', color='magenta')
    plt.legend()
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(tick.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')));

Feature Importance Evaluation¶

The Random Forest Regressor provides a metric for the importance of each of the features in predicting weekly sales. We found that the department is by far the most important feature, followed by the size of the store. All of the other features have much lower importance scores. See the table and graph below.

Features associated with the area surrounding the store, such as the unemployment rate, the weekly temperature, and fuel price, are less important than the department and store size.

An example run of model fitting determined that these were the top four features and their assigned importance scores:

  1. Department -- 0.615
  2. Size -- 0.193
  3. WeekNum -- 0.060
  4. Store -- 0.050

In [19]:
